{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476219"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:42:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:42:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13704"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13704","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13704"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.09,0.08,0.1,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6320"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49122"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6320","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6320"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13704"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34157"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1643"},{"type":"tags","id":"2336"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"3730"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11709"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13487"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13488"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13577"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49122","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/49122"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old boy presents to the Emergency Department with a three-week history of fatigue, pallor, and easy bruising. He has also developed intermittent fevers over the past week. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. On examination, he appears pale with petechiae on his lower limbs and mild hepatosplenomegaly. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98%, and temperature 38.1\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EWhite blood cell count: 85 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4-11)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EHaemoglobin: 72 g/L (120-160)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPlatelet count: 15 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (150-400)\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EPeripheral blood smear: Presence of lymphoblasts\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA bone marrow biopsy is performed and shows 90% lymphoblasts. Flow cytometry reveals that the blasts are positive for CD19, CD22, and CD79a, but negative for CD3 and CD7.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the pathophysiology and classification of this patient\u0027s condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Clonal proliferation of immature B-lymphoid cells in the bone marrow","Clonal proliferation of immature T-lymphoid cells in the thymus","Uncontrolled growth of mature B-lymphocytes in peripheral lymphoid tissues","Malignant transformation of myeloid precursor cells in the bone marrow","Infiltration of the bone marrow by aberrant natural killer cells"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation, laboratory findings, and bone marrow biopsy results are consistent with acute lymphoblastic leukaemia (ALL). The flow cytometry results further classify this as B-cell ALL. The pathophysiology of this condition is best described as \u003Cstrong\u003Eclonal proliferation of immature B-lymphoid cells in the bone marrow\u003C/strong\u003E. This proliferation leads to the displacement of normal haematopoietic cells, resulting in the observed cytopenias (anaemia, thrombocytopenia) and the presence of lymphoblasts in the peripheral blood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EClonal proliferation of immature T-lymphoid cells in the thymus\u003C/strong\u003E describes T-cell ALL, which accounts for about 15% of childhood ALL cases. However, the flow cytometry results in this case (positive for B-cell markers CD19, CD22, and CD79a, and negative for T-cell markers CD3 and CD7) clearly indicate B-cell ALL, which is more common in children.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUncontrolled growth of mature B-lymphocytes in peripheral lymphoid tissues\u003C/strong\u003E is more characteristic of B-cell lymphomas rather than leukaemias. In ALL, the proliferating cells are immature lymphoblasts primarily in the bone marrow, not mature B-cells in peripheral tissues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalignant transformation of myeloid precursor cells in the bone marrow\u003C/strong\u003E describes acute myeloid leukaemia (AML). While AML can present similarly to ALL, the flow cytometry results definitively show a B-cell lineage in this case, ruling out a myeloid origin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInfiltration of the bone marrow by aberrant natural killer cells\u003C/strong\u003E would be seen in aggressive NK-cell leukaemia, a rare condition that typically affects adults and would show different immunophenotypic markers on flow cytometry.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis question tests the ability to integrate clinical presentation with laboratory data, particularly flow cytometry results, to accurately classify leukaemia subtypes. Understanding the significance of specific CD markers in distinguishing between B-cell and T-cell ALL is crucial for correct diagnosis and subsequent treatment planning.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Acute lymphoblastic leukaemia is characterised by the clonal proliferation of immature lymphoid cells in the bone marrow.","B-cell ALL is more common than T-cell ALL in children.","Flow cytometry is crucial for immunophenotyping and distinguishing between B-cell and T-cell ALL."],"references":["Terwilliger T, Abdul-Hay M. Acute lymphoblastic leukemia: a comprehensive review and 2017 update. Blood Cancer J. 2017 Jun 30;7(6):e577. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/28665419/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34157"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13704"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"34157","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/34157"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-07-23T16:55:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-05T12:27:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6320"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"49122"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":""